#chapter(title: "shake my little soul for you")[
  Chloe's jacket slips through her fingers. Max screams loud and long.

  It's drowned out by the screeching winds, the pounding rain, but even
  when her throat gives out her ears can pick up the sickening crack of
  Chloe's body colliding with the rocks below. There's a single moment of
  petrification, where all Max can see is Chloe's limp, soaked form
  splayed across the cliff base. The way her right arm is twisted beyond
  repair. The smears of blood lining the rocks that her head had come into
  contact with on her descent. Then, the sea rises to swallow her whole,
  and Chloe is gone.

  Chloe is #emph[gone];.

  Max glares down at the waves, and prays that Chloe washes up somewhere
  far, far away from here.

  This isn\'t the first time she\'s watched Chloe die. Not by a long shot.
  With her constant rewinding and reliving this past week, Max has seen it
  36 times, with incident marking the 37th. But it was different, this
  time.

  It was all her fault.

  It came purely, entirely, unquestionably from her own stubbornness. 36
  dead Chloe Prices had proved too much for Max, and she\'d been downright
  desperate to keep the girl alive this time around, to find a way to keep
  both her and the Bay safe and sound. But Chloe always was the more
  bullheaded of the two of them. She refused to have Max sacrifice the
  entire town just for her sake. So Max had watched, frozen, as Chloe
  wrenched herself from her grip and tumbled into the sea below.

  Max's next thought is the overwhelming urge to tip herself over the edge
  and follow suit. To put an end to this agonizing cycle. Let the storm
  tear through Arcadia Bay and not do a fucking thing about it.

  But habit takes over, fogs up her brain like thick, acrid smoke and
  before she can even blink Max has her hand raised to rewind. She watches
  the world spin and whirl and mix and blur, sea spray and whipping winds,
  fragmented stone and chunks of debris. There's a sharp pang in the back
  of her head, and she can feel the blood dripping from her nose, but she
  doesn't stop. Ripping pressure erupts at the base of her neck, like a
  thousand of those little needles all stuffed into the one spot, but she
  doesn't stop. Her body aches and pounds and screams for her to stop,
  each individual nerve ripping apart at the seams, yet she does not lower
  her arm until it collapses under the weight of time compounded; leaving
  her panting, crying, bleeding on the ground.

  With clipped breath and shaking arms, Max attempts to pull her phone
  from her jacket pocket. Her face nuzzles into the dirt beneath her, and
  she can see blood dampening the pebbles and patchy grass. Her limbs are
  papery, thin and weak and all too easy to shred, but she finally manages
  to bring the phone to her face. Getting her eyes to focus is another
  matter entirely, though the double vision fades in and out just enough
  for her to read a few numbers-- always numbers, so many numbers, too
  many numbers in her head all the goddamn time.

  10:17PM

  A fit of coughs rattles through her ribcage. More. She needs more.

  05/04/13

  Her heart nearly stops.

  Max makes her decision before she can even fully process what this all
  means. She forces herself to stand and tries her best to ignore the
  resulting roil of vertigo, as well as the steady dribble of blood from
  her nose and taste of iron lingering in her throat. Lurching forward,
  one weak leg in front of the other, each step sending sparks of pain
  rolling up her spine. She tries to pick up speed, she #emph[tries] , but
  there's a limp in her left leg and she only makes it a few blocks past
  Two Whales before she falls to the ground. She catches herself on one
  arm, but her face still scrapes against the sidewalk and she can feel
  the gravel scratching at her cheeks, soon followed by an unbearable
  stinging as dirt and dust are forced into her eyes.

  She wants to scream again. To wail at the top of her lungs, to cry out
  for someone, anyone to help her. But no one can help her. She has to do
  this on her own. She always does. She drags herself back into a standing
  position, continuing her hobble up to Blackwell, hoping in vain to blink
  her vision back to normal and spitting a foul mix of blood and bile into
  the gutter.

  Few people are wandering campus when she makes it, and they all stare
  incredulously as she shuffles past them. A few even call out to ask what
  she's doing or if she needs a ride to the hospital. None of them
  recognize her, of course, but Max doesn't care. All Max cares about is
  getting to Rachel before she can take a single goddamn step out of her
  dorm room.

  She trips twice on the stairs, and she knows that she's trailing blood
  all over the fresh tile flooring, but Max continues her climb
  regardless. She remembers the room number --- Chloe had told her once,
  she doesn't know when or where --- though she winds up not needing it.
  She can see the girl\'s name written in bold, red cursive on the
  whiteboard outside her door.

  And she uses the last of her remaining energy to thunk herself against
  that door, too drained to even lift her hand to knock. Rachel's voice
  floats through, and though it's the first time Max has heard it she
  knows then that Chloe was right, that this girl is an angel.

  "Hello?" she asks, and Max can hear her crossing the room in a huff.
  "Victoria, that better not be your drunk ass trying to get into the
  wrong room again."

  Rachel swings the door open with exceptional vigor and sends max
  tumbling to the floor in the process.

  "Shit, fuck, what the hell--"

  Max looks up at her through strained eyes, Rachel Amber and her ghostly
  afterimage dancing around each other in slow, sickly circles. The weight
  of the situation sinks in. Rachel is here. Rachel is #emph[alive];. Max
  can save her, and save Chloe, and Kate, and put a stop to Jefferson and
  Nathan. She just has to keep track of every little moment, every little
  detail, every molecule of minutia going on around her. But she's tired.
  She's so, so tired. Already yesterday melds with tomorrow, fuses ten
  minutes from now to last Wednesday, mixes junkyard scrap with sunny
  snow.

  "Can you hear me? C'mon, c'mon, talk to me."

  All the different incidents, outcomes and conversations swarm in Max's
  mind and she's hopeless; she's desperate and dying on the Blackwell dorm
  floors and all she can get out are pleas so that's what she does.

  "J-Jefferson," Max wheezes, coughs blood onto the floor beside her.
  "Dangerous. Don't go. Please, please don't go."

  A moment of tense silence follows. "The only place we're going is the
  ER," Rachel answers, distant and grim.

  Panic seizes Max's heart in a quick, crushing grip, and her body
  convulses in kind. "No hospital," she begs, whimpering at the phantom
  smell of disinfectant, the muddled memory of a syringe pinching at her
  neck. She doesn't know how many times it happened. "No hospital. No
  Jefferson."

  She can still feel his hands on her. The heat of the lights, the duct
  tape around her wrists. The cold floor against her face as Jefferson's
  voice swung effortlessly between hazed praise and hellish anger. She can
  still see that photo of Rachel, huddled in the corner, bound but
  furious. The photos of Kate. The photos of herself.

  "Okay, okay, no hospital. Just-- Just try to breathe, alright?"

  Max feels herself being pulled into a sitting position, leaned up
  against a body far studier than her own, warm cloth pressed against her
  face. She shudders through an inhale.

  "That's it, there you go." Rachel's voice treads the line between manic
  concern and stone cold calm, but Max can't get enough of it. Every word
  out of her mouth translates straight into guilt-laden elation.

  #emph[I can save her];. Her mind rejoices, howls out in sweet, sombre
  victory. #emph[I did it. I can save her. I can save them both];.

  "Hey, hey."

  The ceiling rumbles with thunder. The walls flash white and bright.

  "Stay with me, c'mon, stay with me."

  Max's eyes roll back. Her mouth twitches up into a smile.

  The world fades in and out for a little while, a tangled web of sights
  and sounds she left behind spinning and blooming into being. Despite how
  often it\'s happened at this point, Max will never get used to it. One
  minute she's back in that storm, deafening winds and crackling lightning
  there to greet her with open arms. The next, she's in The Dark Room,
  tied to that chair and staring down at the empty space where Victoria
  had been. Another blink, and she's back in the dorms with Rachel's
  signature red and black flannel held to her nose.

  Rachel is on the phone with someone, all traces of her earlier composure
  having vanished. She still has an arm around Max, holding her steady as
  she speaks. "There's blood- Like, #emph[a lot] of blood. And she won't
  stop shaking."

  #emph[Only because of the wind];, Max wants to say. But her throat is
  too tight, and Rachel's voice is so hard to hear over the storm. Or
  maybe that's just the blood rushing in her ears.

  "She-- She just showed up at my door and totally collapsed on me."

  Rachel looks pretty in the rain.

  "She said no hospital. Fuck, man, I don't know. Just get here as quick
  as you can."

  Max won\'t let anything happen to her. Not this time.

  #emph[Think, Max];, #emph[think];, she tells herself, gazing up at the
  cut of Rachel\'s jawline, the calm blue of her feather earring.
  #emph[You need to stop him. You need to save them] . She shifts a
  little, forces her heavy eyelids to stay open, willing her body to get
  back up and run to David\'s office. She hardly moves an inch.

  "Take it easy. Are you back with me?"

  Max shrugs as best she can. It doesn\'t matter to her if she\'s all
  there or not, all that matters is that she gets up.

  "Need to… keep going." It takes a considerable amount of effort to
  form the words, like she\'s wading waist deep in a pool of cold molasses
  just to search for them. She struggles in vain to free herself from
  Rachel\'s grip.

  "Uhm, no the fuck you don\'t," huffs Rachel, utterly flabbergasted and
  keeping Max still with barely any effort at all. "What you need to do
  is rest. And you certainly aren\'t gonna get any here in the palace of
  shitty mattresses and nosy neighbors, so I\'m taking you to a friend\'s
  place."

  She must mistake the desperation in Max\'s expression for fear, because
  she immediately continues, tone hushed and even.

  "No hospital, just a friend. I promise. They\'ve got a first aid kit,
  and the bed over there is #emph[way] comfier than mine. Trust me,
  you\'ll thank me later."

  But she can\'t rest now, no matter how much she may want to. Not when
  she\'s so close. Not when she can save them both. Not when she knows
  there\'s an empty binder with Rachel\'s name on it. "Gotta… help…"

  "#emph[You] need help." Max swears those hazel eyes are glowing,
  haloed, bright enough to scare away any shadow. "You look like you\'ve
  been stuck out in the rain too, you poor thing."

  Max could cry. She probably is, now that she thinks about it. She\'s
  never been so happy to be held in a dead girl\'s arms.

  "Storm," the word tumbles from her lips with no resistance. "Always
  so c-c-cold."

  Rachel makes this sort of horrified, sort of sad expression. Whatever
  she\'s feeling, her voice remains measured and steady. "I\'ll grab you
  something warm, and then we can see about getting you up. Sound good?"

  Slowly, carefully, Rachel loosens her grip, allowing Max to sit on her
  own. Or try to, anyways, the waves of dizziness have yet to fully
  subside and Max has a pit in her stomach like her body thinks it might
  teeter into the ocean at any second, but it\'s nothing she hasn\'t dealt
  with before. She watches through her still swirling vision as Rachel
  rifles through her closet with all the speed and ferocity of a cracked
  out cheetah, pulling out the first sweater she can find and rushing back
  over to Max\'s side. It\'s a hoodie, and though the fabric\'s wear and
  tear is telling of its age it\'s no detriment to its comfort. The inside
  is lined with a soft fleece, and as Rachel zips it up Max can\'t help
  but let out a sigh of relief. It feels like it\'s been years since the
  last time she was warm.

  Rachel keeps talking to her as they make their way down to the parking
  lot, gentle nothings and repetitive reassurances that are probably more
  for herself than for Max. She wards Victoria away with some sort of
  snappy remark, assures Kate that everything will be fine, gives Juliet a
  rushed explanation laced with white lies. Max isn\'t paying much
  attention to her little chameleon display, too preoccupied with plotting
  out her desired order of events.

  First, she\'ll tell David, make sure he stops Jefferson before he can
  lay a hand on Rachel, Kate, or Victoria. Then, once she\'s found the
  courage to look the girl in the eyes after driving her to a suicide she
  can never remember, she\'ll apologize to Chloe, presumably introduce
  herself to Rachel in a less ominous context, and find some way to keep
  them both the hell away from Nathan. Simple. Easy.

  "Yo, Rach. Over here."

  Max freezes. She should have guessed. Who else would Rachel have been on
  the phone with.

  "Chloe, thank fuck, let\'s--"

  "Max?!"

  Shit. Shit shit shit. It wasn\'t supposed to go this way, she didn\'t
  want Chloe to see her like this. Not again. She promised that she
  wouldn\'t. She needs more time, there's never enough time.

  But it\'s alright. She\'ll just rewind and--

  Pain surges between her eyes, searing hot and jagged as the rocks
  beneath the lighthouse. She turned back all of three seconds. Too little
  to do anything meaningful, just enough to cause trouble.

  "Chloe, thank fuck, let\'s-- What the hell? When did she--"

  Rachel is no longer at her side, now lagging a few steps behind. Max can
  hear her talking, but all she sees is Chloe.

  Chloe, with her raggedy jacket and her striking blue hair. Chloe, with
  her gruff, familiar voice and oh so snarky attitude. Chloe, who Max
  loves more than anything. Chloe, who ripped herself from Max\'s arms and
  threw herself into the bay.

  Chloe, alive, breathing, and looking right at her.

  "Max?!"

  Despite it all, relief hits her like a freight train. She gives a weak
  laugh at the comparison --- though it's more akin to a pitiful wheeze
  --- and all of the adrenaline drains from her body in one fell swoop,
  leaving her battered and limp and so, so #emph[happy];. She hits the
  asphalt with an echoing crunch.

  "Oh God, oh God #emph[Max];."

  "Shit, shit, she's bleeding again, fuck."

  It's almost funny, having Chloe and Rachel knelt at her side, staring
  down at her body for once. The world goes dark.

  A groan tumbles from her numb lips. She tries to lift her heavy head.

  "Max! You fucked up my shot!"

  That voice, like ice prickling along her spine. She can't get her body
  to move, to get up, to #emph[run] .

  Not even when the storm rolls over the beachside, the lighthouse
  breaking away into big chunks of concrete all hurtling in her direction.

  Not even when she's got her face mashed up against junkyard trash,
  watching the bullet rip through Chloe's chest, Rachel dead and buried
  beneath them.

  She can hear him pushing the cart closer, the metallic grind and scrape
  of the wheels rolling across the floor, how the one in the top left
  corner squeaks at a slightly higher pitch than all the others.

  "Oh, Max."

  \
  \
  He steps towards her in three slow strides. She knows what he\'s going
  to do. She #emph[knows] , but can\'t do anything to stop it. She can
  never stop him. She\'ll always end up here, under his leering eyes,
  under his horrid touch.

  "You\'re almost more trouble than you\'re worth."

  A hand on her back. A pinch in her neck.

  "Almost."

  Max bolts upright with enough force to send herself crashing to the
  floor in a tangle of blankets and sheets. Her limbs offer their
  complaint by throbbing in pain, but Max is more focused on gasping for
  breath, backing as far away as possible. She has to think of a way out
  while she\'s still sober and conscious, she has to, but her mind
  stutters and fumbles and flickers in and out of that helpless, drug
  induced daze and he\'s going to get her again, he\'s going to touch her
  again, he\'s--

  "Whoa, easy there, Super Max."

  If his voice is cutting ice, then Chloe\'s is bright, blaring sunlight.
  Warm and familiar, scorching and sharp. It cuts in a different way.

  She pries her eyes open, and the first thing she notices is just how
  #emph[blue] Chloe\'s hair is. The dye must have faded by the time
  October came around. Comes around. Whichever.

  "I\'m sorry." The words are heavy on her tongue, despite how many
  times she\'s thought about them, how many times she\'s said them. Her
  throat is raspy and raw, and forcing her brain and vocal chords to work
  in tandem is as laborious as holding a rewind for too long. "S-sorry,
  Chloe. Wasn\'t-- wasn\'t there for you."

  "Are you seriously launching into your grand apology speech right
  now?" Chloe gapes back at her, eyes wide and wild and rimmed with a
  dark purple hue. "Fuck that. Max, what the hell happened to you?"

  Ah, that\'s right. She\'s doing things out of order already. Classic
  Max, fucking things up at every opportunity. "Sorry," she says again,
  like it\'s the only word her body will allow her to say. "I\'m sorry."

  "You need to breathe. Both of you."

  This voice is still new. Uncanny and alien and fascinating enough to
  coax Max into listening.

  "Right," Chloe grits, closing her eyes and letting out a harsh sigh.
  "Thanks, Rach."

  Max trembles through an inhale, feels every inch of her body groan in
  protest to her being alive. A few more half steady breaths allot her
  enough clarity in both mind and vision to see that she\'s in Chloe\'s
  room, sunlight streaming in through the flag draped over the window and
  painting the floors in red and white glow. The posters on the wall, the
  boxes and clutter, the faint smell of weed that\'s always clinging to
  the air, all of it a stark reminder of the lack of danger. And of
  course, Chloe herself, knelt down in front of Max with frantic concern
  written all over her features.

  Her body moves of its own accord, and she practically launches herself
  into Chloe, wrapping her arms around her and holding her close. Holding
  tight, like she should have at the lighthouse.

  "Missed you," she mumbles into the fabric of Chloe\'s tank top, voice
  creaking with the effort it takes to push the words up her aching
  throat. "Missed you so much."

  "I… I missed you too, Max."

  Chloe returns the embrace, cautious and hesitant, and for a few blessed
  moments she actually feels #emph[safe];. No swirling storm, no snapping
  shutters. Just Max and her partner in crime.

  "Here."

  And Rachel. That\'s going to take some getting used to.

  Chloe shifts to the side and instinct slaps Max upside the head in a
  cold rush, leading her to grip the back of the girl\'s shirt in
  white-knuckled anticipation. She needs to keep her here. She needs to
  keep her out of danger.

  "It\'s okay. I\'m not goin\' anywhere." Chloe\'s voice has dropped to
  a murmur, smooth and steady. The kind of tone she used to use to coax
  Max out from under the covers during horror movie marathons. "Max,
  c\'mon. I need you to let me go so we can get up."

  Max doesn\'t want to let go.

  Still, she loosens her grip, lets her arms fall slack and stares holes
  into the floor as Chloe helps her back into bed. She\'s handed a bottle
  of water as Chloe gives her as proper an introduction to Rachel as she
  can, which she proceeds to absolutely devour in hopes the hydration will
  make talking a little easier. All the while, they watch her like a pair
  of nervous hawks. Blue eyes fixated on the sharp jut of her jawbone,
  hazel eyes searching her expression for clues.

  Max manages a small, "Thanks," as she finishes, and Rachel takes the
  empty bottle with a wavering sense of calm. She's clearly shaken up ---
  who wouldn't be after seeing something like that --- but she keeps it
  all under lock and smiling key.

  Chloe, on the other hand, looks as if it\'s taking every fibre of her
  being to keep her cool. Her brows are furrowed, and her left leg is
  jittering about like it\'s late for a meeting. "Max," she breathes,
  "What happened to you?"

  It\'s the second time she\'s asked, and judging by the dangerous glint
  in her eye she isn\'t ready to hear the whole truth. Max will have to be
  careful with her words. Which is kind of a problem considering she only
  seems capable of stammering broken bits and pieces of her internal
  monologue.

  Case in point: the very much private thought of #emph[I got myself
  kidnapped by a perverted egomaniac];, turns into a quivering utterance
  of, "Pervert."

  Which is definitely #emph[not] what Chloe wanted to hear, if the burst
  of anger in her expression is anything to go by. Max heaves a sigh and
  rewinds before Chloe can even open her mouth. This time around the
  sudden failing of her powers feels less like a shot to the forehead and
  more like the usual fizzling migraine, which is a definite improvement.
  It seems she\'s still limited to a few seconds at a time, but that\'s
  enough for now.

  Then it happens again. From #emph[I got caught in a storm];, to just,
  "Caught."

  A second rewind leaves her seeing double, and this time Max chooses to
  stay quiet.

  "Did… Did someone hurt you?"

  She flicks her gaze over to Rachel. It\'s strange to see color in her
  face, to see her blinking and breathing and not lifelessly plastered all
  over the town in monochrome, but Max likes it. That, and she doesn\'t
  want to risk overtaxing herself any more than she already has. She nods,
  small and stiff.

  Chloe pales as she repeatedly curls and unfurls her fists. The question
  comes like concrete crushing through her grit teeth. "Who. Who hurt
  you, Max?"

  Max just shakes her head. She can\'t be honest --- #emph[I hurt me. I
  brought this on myself. I deserve this] --- and she can\'t have Chloe
  flying off the handle and running to try and deal with Jefferson
  herself. She can\'t have Chloe running off #emph[period] . Her heart
  can\'t take it.

  Rachel puts a hand on Chloe\'s shoulder, gives it a light squeeze. "Why
  don\'t you go tell your mom that Max is up," she offers with another
  one of those tempered half-smiles. Her tone suggests it\'s not an
  option.

  Chloe looks between them both, dilemma clear as day on her face, but
  eventually she sighs again and moves to stand. "Yeah, alright," she
  huffs, floorboards creaking as she crosses the room. "I won\'t be
  long," she adds, most definitely for Max\'s sake.

  Rachel watches her leave, listens to her thunking down the stairs, and
  once she seems to think Chloe is far enough she turns back to Max with
  curious fire in her eyes. She doesn\'t speak, not at first. She looks
  Max up and down, tilts her head and leans in for a closer look at her
  face, and Max starts to feel like an ant under the magnifying glass of
  her piercing gaze.

  "Jefferson."

  Even just hearing his name makes Max nauseous.

  "I don\'t know how much of last night you remember, but you told me he
  was dangerous. Did he…?"

  Though left unasked, Rachel\'s question sits cold and heavy in Max\'s
  stomach. A whimper crawls its way out of her throat, and she prays her
  pleading expression will say everything for her.

  "I won\'t tell Chloe, if that\'s what you\'re worried about. Promise."

  Rachel matches her desperate look with one of genuine worry, and Max is
  suddenly very aware of the girl\'s famed reputation as someone you can
  never say no to. And she did keep her promise to not take Max to the
  hospital. Besides, Rachel has a right to know; in some morose, mangled
  way.

  Everyone will find out sooner or later. It'll make national headlines.

  The real issue is that she can\'t answer one way or the other in full
  confidence. He had said he didn\'t do anything, that all he wanted was
  to have his fun posing her, but Max isn\'t exactly trustful of his word.
  She\'ll never wash away the algid burn of his touch, the memory of him
  growling, "#emph[God, those eyes.];" When she finally opens her mouth,
  her voice sounds dull and distant.

  "Pictures." The thought pools thick and bitter on her tongue. She
  keeps her gaze fixed on the blankets. Then, she gestures to her neck.
  "Needle."

  All of that color drains from Rachel\'s face in an instant.

  The sound of hurried footsteps on the stairs draws both of them to
  flinch in the direction of the door, only to see one Joyce Price rushing
  in at the speed of light. She\'s by Max\'s side before she can even
  blink, holding her face in both hands, reaching up to smooth her hair
  back.

  "Oh, Maxine, sweetheart you gave us such a scare last night." Her
  voice washes over Max like the first sip of hot cocoa on a cold day.
  Joyce is the only one who\'s allowed to call her that. "How are you
  feeling?"

  After thinking on it for a moment, Max decides on, "Head hurts."
  Because it does, it feels like the universe reached right into her skull
  and made scrambled eggs of her brain. Not that the rest of her feels any
  better, every molecule of every muscle aches like she tore herself in
  pieces and now her body is trying to sew itself back together. Which she
  probably did, in a weird, complicated metaphysical sense, but it was
  worth it to see Chloe and Rachel alive again.

  "I\'d say. You had such an awful nosebleed when you came in." She
  looks Max over, studies her face, her own expression twisting more and
  more into one of melancholy with each passing second. "You look so much
  older than when I last saw you."

  Something inside of Max snaps at that. The final straw, so to speak. She
  feels decades older than she should be, and God only knows how accurate
  a statement that is. She's rewound and photo-jumped and reset too many
  times to count, peeling back the layers and forcing herself deeper and
  deeper into the rabbit hole. Even now, there\'s that same uncanny
  disconnect of being eighteen in her thirteen year old self\'s body. Like
  she's intruding. Like she's taking someone else's happiness. Like she
  doesn\'t belong here.

  She only vaguely registers the sound of Rachel excusing herself to go
  join Chloe downstairs. She\'s too busy trying not to cry.

  "What happened, baby? Do Ryan and Vanessa know where you\'re at?"

  Maybe Max should feel worse than she does about the fact that she
  hasn\'t even thought of them yet. From their perspective she\'ll have
  vanished from her bedroom overnight and somehow made it back to Arcadia
  Bay all on her own, albeit bloodied and clearly worse for wear. What she
  does feel, at the mention of her parents, at the thought of being back
  in Seattle, is near primal fear.

  "Don\'t wanna go," she begs, all rational thought lost to the prospect
  of being taken away from Chloe. Again. "N-Need to stay here. Please
  don\'t make me go."

  She\'d pat herself on the back for finally managing a full sentence if
  only it didn\'t drain her of so much energy. Her lower lip trembles, and
  her eyes go blurry as the tears spill over. Joyce sits beside her and
  gathers her up in a hug, running a hand up and down her back, telling
  her it\'s alright, everything is alright now. It feels more real when
  someone else is saying it.

  "It\'s okay, sweetheart. No one\'s making you leave," Joyce assures,
  reaching up to stroke Max\'s hair. "You\'re in no shape to be going
  anywhere as it is."

  But Max just cries and cries, powerless to stop the flood of guilt and
  panic and ice cold horror that\'s been festering inside of her for weeks
  and weeks on end. She clings to Joyce like a lifeline, basks in the
  protective warmth of familial bonds she\'s been trying so hard to keep
  intact. Even as her mind wails of how undeserving, how unworthy she is
  after all the times she\'s let Chloe die, all the times David got hurt
  trying to save her.

  Shit, David. She has to tell David. She opens her mouth to try and say
  as much. No sound comes out. Her head throbs in complaint. As Joyce
  pulls back, Max spots a drop of blood on her shirt, and hurries to cover
